    {
        "client_msg_id": "cf5ffbd0-fc44-47d6-b323-69626e06e12c",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "I had a \"job search\" class at the tail end of my college exp and the advice I got from one teacher pretty much justified the entire cost of my college experience :joy:: directly address the skills outlined in the JD and speak to your experience in those areas.\n\nHer recommendation was to actually make a table with two columns:\n1. What you're looking for (each bullet in the JD)\n2. What I can bring (a sentence or two about your experience with that thing)\nI never did this, choosing a more natural, in-line approach. But after some seven odd years of hiring, I can say OMG I WOULD APPRECIATE IT SO MUCH IF CANDIDATES DID THIS!!\n\nIt is so hard trying to suss out if someone has _done the thing_ based on a resume. You will make a hiring managers life so much easier if you just say it.\n\nI would add that I don't think you need to cover every bullet. I would pick the 3-5 bullets in the JD where you are strongest and then talk about your experience.\n\nThis checks a lot of the boxes others on the thread have mentioned:\n• It shows you want the job\n• It shows off your writing abilities\n• It shows that you have thought about what you are uniquely well-positioned to bring to the role\n• It shows that you've done your homework\n• And, content marketing 101, it solves a real problem for your reader! :smile: ",
